            <div type="commentary">
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1">
                        <p>The Welsh Corpus notes that <q>[A]V[I] means either 'grandson' or 'descendant' in ogam Irish. The use of this word and ogam script suggests that the name and patronymic are Irish, but they could very well be Old Welsh...the composition vowel A in the ogam suits Irish</q>(Redknap and Lewis 2007, 242). In the Ogham inscription <q>ILVVETO looks Irish, with Irish genitive in -O...but there are exceptions in Welsh, such as <hi rend="italic">Illtud</hi>...the -O could be due to Hibernicization of a Welsh name. ILVVETO appears to have syncope, but this may be an illusion; the VV may correspond to /uw/ (which should properly be written UV in ogam) or, alternatively, it may be related to the Continental Celtic tribal name <hi rend="italic">Elvetii, Helvetii</hi>. Other etymologies connect it with <hi rend="italic">*wed-</hi> as in Welsh <hi rend="italic">dy-wed-yd</hi>, 'to say', hence 'much-speaking, eloquent' or 'much-spoken-of, famous' or with OI <hi rend="italic">Féth</hi>, gen. <hi rend="italic">Fétho</hi>, '?calm, polished'</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 242-4).</p>
                    </item>
                    <item n="2">
                        <p>The Roman-letter inscription commemorates the same person as the Ogham inscription but in a different formulae. The Welsh Corpus notes that compared with the composition vowel A in the Ogam script, which suits Irish, <q>the O in the Roman letters suits Britonnic, so there has been an attempt to translate the name from one language into the other</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 242). A similar attempt has been made in the 'Bamberg Cryptogram' from Gwynedd (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 242-4).</p>
                    </item>
                </list>
